article.headline: Bulldogs' starting five scores in double figures
article.story: STARKVILLE, Miss. (AP) -- For the first time since the Southeastern Conference season started, (No. 24 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) Mississippi State played 40 minutes of stellar basketball. The Bulldogs' entire starting five scored in double figures and their quick-handed defense forced 21 turnovers in an 82-60 victory over Vanderbilt on Wednesday night. The backcourt of Timmy Bowers and Derrick Zimmerman led the way at both ends for the Bulldogs (14-5, 4-4). Bowers had 14 points and five assists while Zimmerman had 13 points, three steals, seven assists and a blocked shot. Mississippi State began conference play No. 7 in the country and has been dropping ever since. Even in their previous conference wins, the Bulldogs either played well in spurts or had to sweat it out at the end. On this night, they were hardly challenged. "It feels good. It helps our confidence out a lot,'' Bowers said. "We pretty much dominated the whole game. Today, we pretty much got the job done defensively. Offensively, we still got to work on some things, but I think it will come.'' Vanderbilt (10-9, 3-5) had won two straight, but both came at home. The Commodores fell to 0-7 on the road, unable to keep up with the quicker and bigger Bulldogs, who beat them by more than 20 for the third straight time. Mississippi State had 15 steals and turned the Commodores' giveaways into 25 points, many coming in the open court. The Bulldogs shot 57 percent, had six blocked shots and outrebounded Vanderbilt 38-24. "This shouldn't take long,'' Vandy coach Kevin Stallings began his postgame remarks. "We got a thorough butt whipping. We couldn't guard them. We couldn't score, and we couldn't rebound.'' Matt Freije led Vanderbilt with 21 points, including 4-of-9 shooting from 3-point range. Brian Thornton added 13 points. Ontario Harper had 13 points and three steals and Michael Ignerski had 11 points. Mario Austin, Mississippi State's leading scorer, had 14 points, but most came in the final 10 minutes with the Bulldogs already way ahead. The Bulldogs controlled the first half with their defense and transition game. Mississippi State had nine steals among Vanderbilt's 13 turnovers, and built a 36-24 halftime lead. "With the athletes that we've got and the guys that can run and jump like we have, I think we're at our best when we are going up and down as quickly as we can,'' Zimmerman said. Mississippi State pulled away by starting the second half with a 16-6 run sparked by Bowers and Zimmerman. After the Commodores scored the first two points of the half, Bowers hit a 3-pointer. Zimmerman then stole the inbounds pass and hit a layup to make it 41-26. Mississippi State closed the surge with Harper sinking a wide-open 3 and Austin getting free inside for one of the rare times in the game to make it 52-30. Vandy made a mini-run to pull within 61-47 with 10 minutes left, but the Bulldogs' quickly resumed control. Austin finished a runout with a finger roll that made it 63-47 with 9 minutes left. Soon after Michael Ignerski hit a 3 from the top of the circle to make it 68-47. Mississippi State then cruised to its fourth win in the last five games. "I'm most disappointed in that they took the fight to us,'' Stallings said. "We backed up and let them keep taking the fight to us.'' Austin managed only two points and two fouls in the first half. But while the Commodores were collapsing around 6-foot-9 center, five other Bulldogs scored at least five points, led by Harper with eight. "You can't just search and search and search for (Austin) and then turn the ball over,'' Bowers said. "You've got to make basketball plays out there.''
